{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"19b3a05b-4105-4b0f-9125-ba5fa4d751ee","content":"The repository doesn't contain documentation on this topic, but I can answer from general .NET/macOS knowledge:\n\n## Recovering a crash dump on macOS without `createdump`\n\n1. **Enable macOS core dumps:**\n   ```bash\n   ulimit -c unlimited\n   ```\n\n2. **Set the core dump directory** (macOS stores them in `/cores/` by default):\n   ```bash\n   ls /cores/\n   ```\n\n3. **Reproduce the crash** — the OS writes a Mach-O core file (e.g., `/cores/core.<pid>`).\n\n4. **If `/cores/` is empty**, ensure SIP isn't blocking core dumps:\n   ```bash\n   sudo sysctl kern.coredump=1\n   ```\n\n5. **Analyze with `lldb`:**\n   ```bash\n   lldb --core /cores/core.12345 /path/to/your/app\n   ```\n\n6. **For managed stack traces**, load the SOS/dotnet diagnostics plugin in lldb:\n   ```bash\n   (lldb) plugin load /path/to/libsosplugin.dylib\n   (lldb) clrstack\n   ```\n\n**Key notes for NativeAOT:**\n- SOS has limited support for NativeAOT; native symbols in the binary are your primary debugging aid.\n- Publish with `<StripSymbols>false</StripSymbols>` to retain symbol information.\n- Consider enabling `<IlcGenerateMstatFile>true</IlcGenerateMstatFile>` for richer diagnostics.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"0c4254c9-fadc-4264-a379-18ff6656cf51","outputTokens":371,"requestId":"5031:41344:26743F:304CAC:69F554DC"},"id":"bdb5fbbb-d251-4b9b-adbb-f07d7fb75a07","timestamp":"2026-05-02T01:35:40.713Z","parentId":"2de02b33-0dc4-498a-85a0-6cbb2b42f588"}
